Laboratory Lab05 – Containers and Kubernetes¶

Author: Bartłomiej Jamiołkowski

In this Jupyter Notebook, I am presenting the solutions to the Assignments.

Assignments¶

Assignment 1¶

Dockerize AWS-CLI.

a)¶

Creating a Dockerfile with aws-cli, built from source files (using tar.gz file / make).

Using a multi-stage build and small base image, based on Alpine Linux, to create a small image. I used an aws tutorial. I improved dockerfile by having the groff installation removed and the Alpine version concretized.

b)¶

Building an image based on my Dockerfile.

Checking buckets on AWS with container.

Checking the size of the container image.

Assignment 2¶

Kubernetes deployment.

a)¶

Creating a k8s cluster using Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS).

Creating node group for this cluster.

Cluster authentication.

Creating a kubeconfig file for the cluster.

Testing configuration.

b)¶

Using Helm, installing an NFS server and provisioner in the cluster.

Installing Helm.

Installing nfs.

Changing StorageClass.

c)¶

Creating a Persistent Volume Claim which will bind to a NFS Persistent Volume provisioned dynamically by the provisioner installed in the previous step.

Running pvc.yaml .

Checking pvc .

d)¶

Creating a Deployment with a HTTP server (e.g., apache or nginx). The web content directory should be mounted as a volume using the PVC created in the previous step.

Running deployment.

e)¶

Creating a Service associated with the Pod(s) of the HTTP server Deployment.

Checking details about svc.

Checking details about nodes.

Checking security group rules.

f)¶

Creating a Job which mounts the PVC and copies a sample content through the shared NFS PV.

Checking if job is running.

g)¶

Testing the HTTP server by showing the sample web content in a browser.

Testing via WSL

Testing via address bar.
